{"id": "duc04-testb-49:5#16", "contents": "The crisis is not just a matter of the Post Office's financial woes, but also reflects the broader economic problems facing Russia. The country is struggling to cope with a plunging ruble, failing crops, and a government that is struggling to provide basic services. The Railway Ministry, which is also owed millions of rubles by the government, is refusing to carry mail until the Post Office pays its debts. This has led to a standoff between the two institutions, with the Post Office accusing the railroads of trying to dominate the thriving mail-order business. Meanwhile, customers are getting angry, and the situation is becoming increasingly desperate."}
